s read it repeatedly in his later years. And today its lessons are more relevant than ever in a world obsessed with the futile pursuit of youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aOld agevEarly works to 1800. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  a148 BC.  a168 BC.  a202 BC.  a209 BC.  a216 BC.  a280 BC.  a295 BC.  a380 BC.  a480 BC.  a509 BC.  a5th century BC.  aAequi.  aAgriculture.  aAncient Rome.  aAppius Claudius Caecus.  aAppius Claudius.  aAugur.  aBattle of Cannae.  aBattle of Pydna.  aBattle of Zama.  aCarthago delenda est.  aCato the Elder.  aCethegus.  aCleanthes.  aCognomen.  aCyrus the Great.  aCyrus the Younger.  aDarius II.  aDe Legibus.  aDe re publica.  aDemocritus.  aDiogenes of Babylon.  aEnnius.  aEnthusiasm.  aFabius Maximus.  aFlaccus.  aGaius Fabricius Luscinus.  aGaius Flaminius.  aGaius Laelius.  aGaius Pontius.  aGaius Servilius Ahala.  aGnaeus (praenomen).  aGorgias.  aGreek literature.  aHesiod.  aHis Family.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIsocrates.  aKing of Rome.  aLaertes.  aLivius Andronicus.  aLucius Aemilius Paullus (consul 219 BC).  aLucius Caecilius Metellus (consul 251 BC).  aLucius Junius Brutus.  aLucius Quinctius Cincinnatus.  aManius Curius Dentatus.  aManure.  aMarcus Atilius Regulus.  aMarcus Livius Salinator.  aMarcus Porcius Cato (son of Cato the Younger).  aMasinissa.  aMiddle Ages.  aMiddle age.  aMilitary tribune.  aMilo of Croton.  aMiser.  aNaevius.  aOedipus at Colonus.  aPelias.  aPhilosopher.  aPlautus.  aPlaywright.  aPublius Cornelius Scipio.  aQuintus Fabius Maximus.  aRhetoric.  aRoman consul.  aRoman dictator.  aSabines.  aScipio Aemilianus.  aScipio Africanus.  aSeleucid Empire.  aS